Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Halve the @bell pepper{1}(halved, cored and thinly sliced), remove the core and seeds and thinly slice. Peel and finely grate the @ginger{½}(peeled and finely grated), roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Fill and boil your kettle.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} over high heat. Once the pan is hot, add the @British beef mince{240%g} and fry until golden brown, ~{4-5%minutes}. Break it up with a #spoon{} as it cooks.

Meanwhile, pour the @water{300%ml} for the rice into a #saucepan{} and bring back to the boil. Stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g} and @salt{¼%tsp}. Lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, when the mince is browned, lower the heat then add the red onion and red pepper. Cook until softened, ~{6-8%minutes}, stirring occasionally. Next add the ginger, @Thai style spice mix{1} and the @chicken stock powder{1}. Add the @water{100%ml} and stir in the @sugar snap peas{80}(mangetout). Simmer until the liquid has reduced by half and the mangetout are tender, ~{4-5%minutes}.

While everything cooks, zest and halve the @lime{½}. When the beef is ready stir through the @ketjap manis{25%ml}, a squeeze of lime juice and half the coriander. Remove from the heat, taste and add @salt{} and @pepper{} if necessary. Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir through the lime zest. Get ready to serve.

Share the rice between your #bowls{} and serve the beef on top. Finish with a sprinkle of the remaining coriander. Chop the remaining lime into wedges and serve alongside for anyone who likes things extra zesty.

> Be careful with the Thai style spice mix - add less if you don't like spice!